===Noun===
{{en-noun|abiogeneses}}

# {{lb|en|evolutionary theory}} The [[origination]] of [[living]] [[organism]]s from [[lifeless]] matter; such [[genesis]] as does not [[involve]] the action of living [[parent#Noun|parents]]; [[spontaneous generation]]. {{defdate|from 1870}}
#* {{quote-journal|author=[Thomas Henry Huxley]|authorlink=Thomas Huxley|title=The President’s Address|magazine=[[w:The Athenaeum (British magazine)|The Athenæum: Journal of English and Foreign Literature, Science, the Fine Arts, Music and the Drama]]|location=London|publisher=Printed by Edward J. Francis, Took's Court, {{w|Chancery Lane}}, published at the office, 20, Wellington Street, [[w:Strand, London|Strand]], W.C., by John Francis. [...]|date=17 September 1870|issue=2238|page=374|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=Dk9DAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA374|columns=2–3|oclc=956082422|passage=And thus the hypothesis that living matter always arises by the agency of pre-existing living matter, took definite shape; {{...}} It will be necessary for me to refer to this hypothesis so frequently, that, to save circumlocution, I shall call it the hypothesis of ''Biogenesis''; and I shall term the contrary doctrine—that living matter may be produced by not living matter—the hypothesis of '''''Abiogenesis'''''.}}

